Disappointed and confused
Sep 2024 • Solo
I didn't know what to expect with this show, but to some degree I think that is by design, however that is not always the best thing especially for a Vegas show. Additionally, I had some discomfort with the storytelling.

[SPOILERS]

You are essentially ushered between various rooms that feel like a non-scary haunted house, and short live vignettes play out in each room.

Logistically it was confusing both in booking and experience. When booking tickets, it's hard to understand the difference between Wanderlust and House of Shattered Prisms. However, House of Shattered Prisms is the only "show," and Wanderlust means you can walk through the set during the daytime when the show is not happening.

In the waiting room, there is pre-show video that explains that creativity has been lost and must be found again by reconnecting with our inner child, interspersed with clips of millennial nostalgia like Care Bears and the Never Ending Story. When the "show" begins, it starts with a puppet that makes jokes about swinging with a couple in attendance. I have no issue with raunch, but the tone seemed so irrelevant to the alleged storyline. Immediately the tone switched back to the "story," the artist and his wife.

Without going through a beat-by-beat, one of the major problems that made me very uncomfortable were the racial undertones.

The protagonist, the artist, is a white male whose wife appeared to have no agency. During the opening sequences, the artist is drawing and dancing to cheerful music and his wife does a ballet. Then, the "evil" force enters the room through a trash can which is a black man who dances to hip hop, and steals the creativity of the artist. Then, the story progresses to "the balance between darkness and light must be restored." White is light and black is darkness.

In another room of the show later, a white female is dancing sort of like an acrobatic ballet. Then the "evil" black antagonist comes in and she is taken over - she sheds her clothing and the music turns from ballet to techno and she starts doing stripper moves, as if that is the visualization of her corruption or loss of creativity?

The company behind this show, Kaleidoco, is essentially an AI company, and have given TED talks about AI/AR/Metaverse technology. Honestly this show felt like unsurprising output along the unfortunate trajectory of where we are at with AI. AI can't come up with anything new, so at best it regurgitates what we already know and at worst it reinforces social stereotypes and biases that are so deeply embedded that we barely stop to notice.

An AI invested/generated show about losing our creativity and needing to reconnect with it muddles that message when the purpose behind AI is to extract and squander human creativity to increase profit for corporations and investors.

I definitely think the performers gave it their best with the material that they had to work with. However, $75 a ticket is well on the way toward a Cirque ticket price which has a much higher production and performance value, and will do more to inspire your creativity.

For the producers, I would seriously consider how this show would be experience by a person of color - using hip hop and blackness to portray "evil" and "corruption" is not okay.

Mind-bending walk in a dark wonderland!
Jun 2024 • Couples
This is truly the most novel and visually engaging experience I had with any event besides Cirque du Soleil while in Vegas.
Tickets for the cast show in the evening seemed too expensive for what it looked like you paid for and didn’t fit into our schedule. Taking the time in the day allowed us to explore at our own pace, with no set entry time and hardly any other people around.
Handheld interactive mirror animation sequences and a little quest to locate particular images throughout the multiple rooms give purpose to those who might get lost in a fantasy storyline. But getting lost is probably a good idea!! The rolling animations being broadcast on all surfaces bring to life sets of dark, weird and incredibly beautiful characters and monsters. Every wall is literally covered with things to see or read, from bits of thought-provoking wisdom, to riddles, to fragmented pieces describing the 2.5th dimensional reality Bering presented. There is a long hallway of captured animated sequences we could have spent 30-minutes just watching in awe! Add to that the fun of being able to add our own (very temporary) light graffiti, throwing wads of paper at walls to generate new characters and the uncertainty never knowing what the next room would hold and it added up to a mind-bending hour+ of time in another world.
